Accept.name: Accept

used in certain circumstances to indicate the context into which the `object`
has been accepted.

Activity.name: Activity
Activity.doc:
An Activity is a subtype of {@link Object} that describes some form of action
that may happen, is currently happening, or has already happened.
The {@link Activity} type itself serves as an abstract base type for all types
of activities.  It is important to note that the {@link Activity} type itself
does not carry any specific semantics about the kind of action being taken.
Activity.label: Activity

Activity.getTarget().name: Activity.prototype.getTarget
Activity.getTarget().doc:
Describes the indirect object, or target, of the activity.  The precise
meaning of the target is largely dependent on the type of action being
described but will often be the object of the English preposition "to".
For instance, in the activity "John added a movie to his wishlist",
the target of the activity is John's wishlist.  An activity can have more
than one target.
Activity.getTarget().label: Activity.getTarget()

directed.  The precise meaning of the origin is the object of the English
preposition "from". For instance, in the activity "John moved an item to
List B from List A", the origin of the activity is "List A".

Application.manuallyApprovesFollowers().name: Application.prototype.manuallyApprovesFollowers
Application.manuallyApprovesFollowers().doc:
When `true`, conveys that for this actor, follow requests are not usually
automatically approved, but instead are examined by a person who may accept
or reject the request, at some time in the future.  Setting of `false`
conveys no information and may be ignored.  This information is typically
used to affect display of accounts, such as showing an account as private or
locked.
Application.manuallyApprovesFollowers().label: Application.manuallyApprovesFollowers()

Application.getInbox().name: Application.prototype.getInbox
Application.getInbox().doc:
The inbox stream contains all activities received by the actor.  The server
SHOULD filter content according to the requester's permission.  In general,
the owner of an inbox is likely to be able to access all of their inbox
contents.  Depending on access control, some other content may be public,
whereas other content may require authentication for non-owner users,
if they can access the inbox at all.

The server MUST perform de-duplication of activities returned by the inbox.
Duplication can occur if an activity is addressed both to an actor's
followers, and a specific actor who also follows the recipient actor,
and the server has failed to de-duplicate the recipients list.
Such deduplication MUST be performed by comparing the `id` of the activities
and dropping any activities already seen.
Application.getInbox().label: Application.getInbox()

Application.getOutbox().name: Application.prototype.getOutbox
Application.getOutbox().doc:
The outbox stream contains activities the user has published,
subject to the ability of the requestor to retrieve the activity
(that is, the contents of the outbox are filtered by the permissions of
the person reading it).  If a user submits a request without
[Authorization](https://www.w3.org/TR/activitypub/#authorization)
the server should respond with all of the
[Public](https://www.w3.org/TR/activitypub/#public-addressing) posts.
This could potentially be all relevant objects published by the user,
though the number of available items is left to the discretion of those
implementing and deploying the server.
Application.getOutbox().label: Application.getOutbox()

Block.name: Block
Block.doc:
Indicates that the `actor` is blocking the `object`.  Blocking is a stronger
form of {@link Ignore}.  The typical use is to support social systems that
allow one user to block activities or content of other users.  The `target`
and `origin` typically have no defined meaning.

ChatMessage.name: ChatMessage
ChatMessage.doc:
`ChatMessage`s are the messages sent in 1-on-1 chats.  They are similar to
{@link Note}s, but the addressing is done by having a single AP actor in
the `to` field.  Addressing multiple actors is not allowed.  These messages
are always private, there is no public version of them.  They are created with
a {@link Create} activity.
ChatMessage.label: ChatMessage

ChatMessage.quoteUrl().name: ChatMessage.prototype.quoteUrl
ChatMessage.quoteUrl().doc:
The URI of the ActivityStreams object that this object quotes.

This property sets three JSON-LD properties at once under the hood:

1. https://www.w3.org/ns/activitystreams#quoteUrl
2. https://misskey-hub.net/ns#_misskey_quote
3. http://fedibird.com/ns#quoteUri

When a JSON-LD object is parsed, this property is filled with one of
the values of those three properties in order.
ChatMessage.quoteUrl().label: ChatMessage.quoteUrl()

Context.routeActivity().name: Context.routeActivity
Context.routeActivity().doc:
Manually routes an activity to the appropriate inbox listener.

It is useful for routing an activity that is not received from the network,
or for routing an activity that is enclosed in another activity.

Note that the activity will be verified if it has Object Integrity Proofs
or is equivalent to the actual remote object.  If the activity is not
verified, it will be rejected.

Endpoints.sharedInbox().name: Endpoints.prototype.sharedInbox
Endpoints.sharedInbox().doc:
An optional endpoint [used for wide delivery of publicly addressed
activities and activities sent to
followers](https://www.w3.org/TR/activitypub/#shared-inbox-delivery).
`sharedInbox` endpoints SHOULD also be publicly readable
{@link OrderedCollection} objects containing objects addressed to the
[Public](https://www.w3.org/TR/activitypub/#public-addressing) special
collection.  Reading from the `sharedInbox` endpoint MUST NOT present
objects which are not addressed to the `Public`` endpoint.
Endpoints.sharedInbox().label: Endpoints.sharedInbox()

GetNodeInfoOptions.parse.name: GetNodeInfoOptions.parse
GetNodeInfoOptions.parse.doc:
How strictly to parse the NodeInfo document.

 -  `"strict"`: Parse the NodeInfo document strictly.  If the document is
    invalid, `undefined` is returned.  This is the default.
 -  `"best-effort"`: Try to parse the NodeInfo document even if it is
    invalid.
 -  `"none"`: Do not parse the NodeInfo document.  The function will return
    the raw JSON value.
GetNodeInfoOptions.parse.label: GetNodeInfoOptions.parse

Group.manuallyApprovesFollowers().name: Group.prototype.manuallyApprovesFollowers
Group.manuallyApprovesFollowers().doc:
When `true`, conveys that for this actor, follow requests are not usually
automatically approved, but instead are examined by a person who may accept
or reject the request, at some time in the future.  Setting of `false`
conveys no information and may be ignored.  This information is typically
used to affect display of accounts, such as showing an account as private or
locked.
Group.manuallyApprovesFollowers().label: Group.manuallyApprovesFollowers()

Group.getInbox().name: Group.prototype.getInbox
Group.getInbox().doc:
The inbox stream contains all activities received by the actor.  The server
SHOULD filter content according to the requester's permission.  In general,
the owner of an inbox is likely to be able to access all of their inbox
contents.  Depending on access control, some other content may be public,
whereas other content may require authentication for non-owner users,
if they can access the inbox at all.

The server MUST perform de-duplication of activities returned by the inbox.
Duplication can occur if an activity is addressed both to an actor's
followers, and a specific actor who also follows the recipient actor,
and the server has failed to de-duplicate the recipients list.
Such deduplication MUST be performed by comparing the `id` of the activities
and dropping any activities already seen.
Group.getInbox().label: Group.getInbox()

Group.getOutbox().name: Group.prototype.getOutbox
Group.getOutbox().doc:
The outbox stream contains activities the user has published,
subject to the ability of the requestor to retrieve the activity
(that is, the contents of the outbox are filtered by the permissions of
the person reading it).  If a user submits a request without
[Authorization](https://www.w3.org/TR/activitypub/#authorization)
the server should respond with all of the
[Public](https://www.w3.org/TR/activitypub/#public-addressing) posts.
This could potentially be all relevant objects published by the user,
though the number of available items is left to the discretion of those
implementing and deploying the server.
Group.getOutbox().label: Group.getOutbox()

for the actor, added as a
[side effect](https://www.w3.org/TR/activitypub/#follow-activity-outbox).
This is where one would find a list of all the actors that are following
the actor.  The `followers` collection MUST be either
an {@link OrderedCollection} or a {@link Collection} and MAY be filtered on
privileges of an authenticated user or as appropriate when no authentication
is given.
Group.getFollowers.label: Group.getFollowers

InboxContext.forwardActivity().name: InboxContext.forwardActivity
InboxContext.forwardActivity().doc:
Forwards a received activity to the recipients' inboxes.  The forwarded
activity will be signed in HTTP Signatures by the forwarder, but its
payload will not be modified, i.e., Linked Data Signatures and Object
Integrity Proofs will not be added.  Therefore, if the activity is not
signed (i.e., it has neither Linked Data Signatures nor Object Integrity
Proofs), the recipient probably will not trust the activity.
InboxContext.forwardActivity().label: InboxContext.forwardActivity()

where `urlPattern` is either a string, a {@link URL}, or

Link.name: Link
Link.doc:
A Link is an indirect, qualified reference to a resource identified by a URL.
The fundamental model for links is established by RFC 5988. Many of the
properties defined by the Activity Vocabulary allow values that are either
instances of {@link Object} or {@link Link}. When a {@link Link} is used,
it establishes a qualified relation connecting the subject (the containing
object) to the resource identified by the `href`. Properties of
the {@link Link} are properties of the reference as opposed to properties of
the resource.
Link.label: Link

Link.rel().name: Link.prototype.rel
Link.rel().doc:
A link relation associated with a {@link Link}. The value MUST conform to
both the HTML5 and RFC 5988 "link relation" definitions.

In the HTML5, any string not containing the space (U+0020), tab (U+0009),
LF (U+000A), FF (U+000C), CR (U+000D) or comma (U+002C) characters can
be used as a valid link relation.

Object.getContexts().name: Object.prototype.getContexts
Object.getContexts().doc:
Identifies the context within which the object exists or an activity was
performed.

The notion of "context" used is intentionally vague.  The intended function
is to serve as a means of grouping objects and activities that share
a common originating context or purpose.  An example could be all activities
relating to a common project or event.

Object.getShares().name: Object.prototype.getShares
Object.getShares().doc:
Every object *may* have a `shares` collection. This is a list of all
{@link Announce} activities with this object as the `object` property,
added as a [side effect]. The `shares` collection *must* be either
an {@link OrderedCollection} or a {@link Collection} and *may* be filtered
on privileges of an authenticated user or as appropriate
when no authentication is given.

[side effect]: https://www.w3.org/TR/activitypub/#announce-activity-inbox

Object.duration().name: Object.prototype.duration
Object.duration().doc:
When the object describes a time-bound resource, such as an audio or video,
a meeting, etc, the `duration` property indicates the object's approximate
duration.  The value MUST be expressed as an `xsd:duration` as defined by
W3C XML Schema Definition Language (XSD) 1.1 Part 2: DataTypes, section
3.3.6 (e.g. a period of 5 seconds is represented as `PT5S`).
Object.duration().label: Object.duration()

Organization.manuallyApprovesFollowers().name: Organization.prototype.manuallyApprovesFollowers
Organization.manuallyApprovesFollowers().doc:
When `true`, conveys that for this actor, follow requests are not usually
automatically approved, but instead are examined by a person who may accept
or reject the request, at some time in the future.  Setting of `false`
conveys no information and may be ignored.  This information is typically
used to affect display of accounts, such as showing an account as private or
locked.
Organization.manuallyApprovesFollowers().label: Organization.manuallyApprovesFollowers()

Organization.manuallyApprovesFollowers.name: Organization.prototype.manuallyApprovesFollowers
Organization.manuallyApprovesFollowers.doc:
When `true`, conveys that for this actor, follow requests are not usually
automatically approved, but instead are examined by a person who may accept
or reject the request, at some time in the future.  Setting of `false`
conveys no information and may be ignored.  This information is typically
used to affect display of accounts, such as showing an account as private or
locked.
Organization.manuallyApprovesFollowers.label: Organization.manuallyApprovesFollowers

Organization.getInbox().name: Organization.prototype.getInbox
Organization.getInbox().doc:
The inbox stream contains all activities received by the actor.  The server
SHOULD filter content according to the requester's permission.  In general,
the owner of an inbox is likely to be able to access all of their inbox
contents.  Depending on access control, some other content may be public,
whereas other content may require authentication for non-owner users,
if they can access the inbox at all.

The server MUST perform de-duplication of activities returned by the inbox.
Duplication can occur if an activity is addressed both to an actor's
followers, and a specific actor who also follows the recipient actor,
and the server has failed to de-duplicate the recipients list.
Such deduplication MUST be performed by comparing the `id` of the activities
and dropping any activities already seen.
Organization.getInbox().label: Organization.getInbox()

Organization.getOutbox().name: Organization.prototype.getOutbox
Organization.getOutbox().doc:
The outbox stream contains activities the user has published,
subject to the ability of the requestor to retrieve the activity
(that is, the contents of the outbox are filtered by the permissions of
the person reading it).  If a user submits a request without
[Authorization](https://www.w3.org/TR/activitypub/#authorization)
the server should respond with all of the
[Public](https://www.w3.org/TR/activitypub/#public-addressing) posts.
This could potentially be all relevant objects published by the user,
though the number of available items is left to the discretion of those
implementing and deploying the server.
Organization.getOutbox().label: Organization.getOutbox()

Person.manuallyApprovesFollowers().name: Person.prototype.manuallyApprovesFollowers
Person.manuallyApprovesFollowers().doc:
When `true`, conveys that for this actor, follow requests are not usually
automatically approved, but instead are examined by a person who may accept
or reject the request, at some time in the future.  Setting of `false`
conveys no information and may be ignored.  This information is typically
used to affect display of accounts, such as showing an account as private or
locked.
Person.manuallyApprovesFollowers().label: Person.manuallyApprovesFollowers()

Person.getInbox().name: Person.prototype.getInbox
Person.getInbox().doc:
The inbox stream contains all activities received by the actor.  The server
SHOULD filter content according to the requester's permission.  In general,
the owner of an inbox is likely to be able to access all of their inbox
contents.  Depending on access control, some other content may be public,
whereas other content may require authentication for non-owner users,
if they can access the inbox at all.

The server MUST perform de-duplication of activities returned by the inbox.
Duplication can occur if an activity is addressed both to an actor's
followers, and a specific actor who also follows the recipient actor,
and the server has failed to de-duplicate the recipients list.
Such deduplication MUST be performed by comparing the `id` of the activities
and dropping any activities already seen.
Person.getInbox().label: Person.getInbox()

Person.getOutbox().name: Person.prototype.getOutbox
Person.getOutbox().doc:
The outbox stream contains activities the user has published,
subject to the ability of the requestor to retrieve the activity
(that is, the contents of the outbox are filtered by the permissions of
the person reading it).  If a user submits a request without
[Authorization](https://www.w3.org/TR/activitypub/#authorization)
the server should respond with all of the
[Public](https://www.w3.org/TR/activitypub/#public-addressing) posts.
This could potentially be all relevant objects published by the user,
though the number of available items is left to the discretion of those
implementing and deploying the server.
Person.getOutbox().label: Person.getOutbox()

for the actor, added as a
[side effect](https://www.w3.org/TR/activitypub/#follow-activity-outbox).

the actor.  The `followers` collection MUST be either
an {@link OrderedCollection} or a {@link Collection} and MAY be filtered on
privileges of an authenticated user or as appropriate when no authentication
is given.

Question.name: Question
Question.doc:
Represents a question being asked.  Question objects are an extension of
{@link IntransitiveActivity}.  That is, the Question object is an Activity,
but the direct object is the question itself and therefore it would not
contain an `object` property.

Either of the `inclusiveOptions` and `exclusiveOptions` properties *may* be
used to express possible answers, but a Question object *must not* have both
properties.
Question.label: Question

used to express possible answers, but a Question object *must not* have both
properties.

Question.quoteUrl().name: Question.prototype.quoteUrl
Question.quoteUrl().doc:
The URI of the ActivityStreams object that this object quotes.

This property sets three JSON-LD properties at once under the hood:

1. https://www.w3.org/ns/activitystreams#quoteUrl
2. https://misskey-hub.net/ns#_misskey_quote
3. http://fedibird.com/ns#quoteUri

When a JSON-LD object is parsed, this property is filled with one of
the values of those three properties in order.

Service.manuallyApprovesFollowers().name: Service.prototype.manuallyApprovesFollowers
Service.manuallyApprovesFollowers().doc:
When `true`, conveys that for this actor, follow requests are not usually
automatically approved, but instead are examined by a person who may accept
or reject the request, at some time in the future.  Setting of `false`
conveys no information and may be ignored.  This information is typically
used to affect display of accounts, such as showing an account as private or
locked.
Service.manuallyApprovesFollowers().label: Service.manuallyApprovesFollowers()

Service.getInbox().name: Service.prototype.getInbox
Service.getInbox().doc:
The inbox stream contains all activities received by the actor.  The server
SHOULD filter content according to the requester's permission.  In general,
the owner of an inbox is likely to be able to access all of their inbox
contents.  Depending on access control, some other content may be public,
whereas other content may require authentication for non-owner users,
if they can access the inbox at all.

The server MUST perform de-duplication of activities returned by the inbox.
Duplication can occur if an activity is addressed both to an actor's
followers, and a specific actor who also follows the recipient actor,
and the server has failed to de-duplicate the recipients list.
Such deduplication MUST be performed by comparing the `id` of the activities
and dropping any activities already seen.
Service.getInbox().label: Service.getInbox()

Service.getOutbox().name: Service.prototype.getOutbox
Service.getOutbox().doc:
The outbox stream contains activities the user has published,
subject to the ability of the requestor to retrieve the activity
(that is, the contents of the outbox are filtered by the permissions of
the person reading it).  If a user submits a request without
[Authorization](https://www.w3.org/TR/activitypub/#authorization)
the server should respond with all of the
[Public](https://www.w3.org/TR/activitypub/#public-addressing) posts.
This could potentially be all relevant objects published by the user,
though the number of available items is left to the discretion of those
implementing and deploying the server.
Service.getOutbox().label: Service.getOutbox()

Service.getFollowing().name: Service.prototype.getFollowing
Service.getFollowing().doc:
This is a list of everybody that the actor has followed, added as a
[side effect](https://www.w3.org/TR/activitypub/#follow-activity-outbox).
The `following` collection MUST be either an {@link OrderedCollection}
or a {@link Collection} and MAY be filtered on privileges of
an authenticated user or as appropriate when no authentication is given.

verifyJsonLd().name: verifyJsonLd
verifyJsonLd().doc:
Verify the authenticity of the given JSON-LD document using Linked Data
Signatures.  If the document is signed, this function verifies the signature
and checks if the document is attributed to the owner of the public key.
If the document is not signed, this function returns `false`.
verifyJsonLd().label: verifyJsonLd()

verifyObject().name: verifyObject
verifyObject().doc:
Verifies the given object.  It will verify all the proofs in the object,
and succeed only if all the proofs are valid and all attributions and
actors are authenticated by the proofs.
verifyObject().label: verifyObject()

verifyProof().name: verifyProof
verifyProof().doc: Verifies the given proof for the object.
verifyProof().label: verifyProof()

verifyRequest().name: verifyRequest
verifyRequest().doc:
Verifies the signature of a request.

Note that this function consumes the request body, so it should not be used
if the request body is already consumed.  Consuming the request body after
calling this function is okay, since this function clones the request
under the hood.
verifyRequest().label: verifyRequest()

verifySignature().name: verifySignature
verifySignature().doc: Verifies Linked Data Signatures of the given JSON-LD document.
verifySignature().label: verifySignature()

autoIdAssigner().name: autoIdAssigner
autoIdAssigner().doc:
An activity transformer that assigns a new random ID to an activity if it
does not already have one.  This is useful for ensuring that activities
have an ID before they are sent to other servers.

The generated ID is an origin URI with a fragment which contains an activity
type name with a random UUID:

```
https://example.com/#Follow/12345678-1234-5678-1234-567812345678
```
autoIdAssigner().label: autoIdAssigner()

CreateFederationOptions.queue.name: CreateFederationOptions.queue
CreateFederationOptions.queue.doc:
The message queue for sending and receiving activities.  If not provided,
activities will not be queued and will be processed immediately.

If a `MessageQueue` is provided, both the `inbox` and `outbox` queues
will be set to the same queue.

If a `FederationQueueOptions` object is provided, you can set the queues
separately (since Fedify 1.3.0).
CreateFederationOptions.queue.label: CreateFederationOptions.queue

~CreateFederationOptions.queue.name: CreateFederationOptions.queue
~CreateFederationOptions.queue.doc:
The message queue for sending and receiving activities.  If not provided,

If a `MessageQueue` is provided, both the `inbox` and `outbox` queues
will be set to the same queue.

If a `FederationQueueOptions` object is provided, you can set the queues
separately (since Fedify 1.3.0).
~CreateFederationOptions.queue.label: queue

CreateFederationOptions.manuallyStartQue.name: CreateFederationOptions.manuallyStartQueue
CreateFederationOptions.manuallyStartQue.doc:
Whether to start the task queue manually or automatically.

If `true`, the task queue will not start automatically and you need to
manually start it by calling the {@link Federation.startQueue} method.

If `false`, the task queue will start automatically as soon as
the first task is enqueued.

By default, the queue starts automatically.
CreateFederationOptions.manuallyStartQue.label: CreateFederationOptions.manuallyStartQueue

~CreateFederationOptions.manuallyStartQu.name: CreateFederationOptions.manuallyStartQueue
~CreateFederationOptions.manuallyStartQu.doc:
Whether to start the task queue manually or automatically.

If `true`, the task queue will not start automatically and you need to
manually start it by calling the {@link Federation.startQueue} method.

If `false`, the task queue will start automatically as soon as
the first task is enqueued.

By default, the queue starts automatically.
~CreateFederationOptions.manuallyStartQu.label: manuallyStartQueue

CreateFederationOptions.onOutboxError.name: CreateFederationOptions.onOutboxError
CreateFederationOptions.onOutboxError.doc:
A callback that handles errors during outbox processing.  Note that this
callback can be called multiple times for the same activity, because
the delivery is retried according to the backoff schedule until it
succeeds or reaches the maximum retry count.

If any errors are thrown in this callback, they are ignored.
CreateFederationOptions.onOutboxError.label: CreateFederationOptions.onOutboxError

~CreateFederationOptions.onOutboxError.name: CreateFederationOptions.onOutboxError
~CreateFederationOptions.onOutboxError.doc:

succeeds or reaches the maximum retry count.

CreateFederationOptions.signatureTimeWin.name: CreateFederationOptions.signatureTimeWindow
CreateFederationOptions.signatureTimeWin.doc:
The time window for verifying HTTP Signatures of incoming requests.  If the
request is older or newer than this window, it is rejected.  Or if it is
`false`, the request's timestamp is not checked at all.

By default, the window is an hour.
CreateFederationOptions.signatureTimeWin.label: CreateFederationOptions.signatureTimeWindow

~CreateFederationOptions.signatureTimeWi.name: CreateFederationOptions.signatureTimeWindow

The time window for verifying HTTP Signatures of incoming requests.  If the
request is older or newer than this window, it is rejected.  Or if it is

CreateFederationOptions.skipSignatureVer.name: CreateFederationOptions.skipSignatureVerification
CreateFederationOptions.skipSignatureVer.doc:
Whether to skip HTTP Signatures verification for incoming activities.
This is useful for testing purposes, but should not be used in production.

By default, this is `false` (i.e., signatures are verified).
CreateFederationOptions.skipSignatureVer.label: CreateFederationOptions.skipSignatureVerification

CreateFederationOptions.outboxRetryPolic.name: CreateFederationOptions.outboxRetryPolicy
CreateFederationOptions.outboxRetryPolic.doc:
The retry policy for sending activities to recipients' inboxes.
By default, this uses an exponential backoff strategy with a maximum of
10 attempts and a maximum delay of 12 hours.
CreateFederationOptions.outboxRetryPolic.label: CreateFederationOptions.outboxRetryPolicy

~CreateFederationOptions.outboxRetryPoli.name: CreateFederationOptions.outboxRetryPolicy

CreateFederationOptions.inboxRetryPolicy.name: CreateFederationOptions.inboxRetryPolicy
CreateFederationOptions.inboxRetryPolicy.doc:

ParallelMessageQueue.name: ParallelMessageQueue
ParallelMessageQueue.doc:
A message queue that processes messages in parallel.  It takes another
{@link MessageQueue}, and processes messages in parallel up to a certain
number of workers.

Actually, it's rather a decorator than a queue itself.

Note that the workers do not run in truly parallel, in the sense that they
are not running in separate threads or processes.  They are running in the
same process, but are scheduled to run in parallel.  Hence, this is useful
for I/O-bound tasks, but not for CPU-bound tasks, which is okay for Fedify's
workloads.
ParallelMessageQueue.label: ParallelMessageQueue

are not running in separate threads or processes.  They are running in the
same process, but are scheduled to run in parallel.  Hence, this is useful
for I/O-bound tasks, but not for CPU-bound tasks, which is okay for Fedify's
workloads.
new ParallelMessageQueue.label: new ParallelMessageQueue

createExponentialBackoffPolicy().name: createExponentialBackoffPolicy
createExponentialBackoffPolicy().doc:
Creates an exponential backoff retry policy.  The delay between retries
starts at the `initialDelay` and is multiplied by the `factor` for each
subsequent retry, up to the `maxDelay`.  The policy will give up after
`maxAttempts` attempts.  The actual delay is randomized to avoid
synchronization (jitter).
createExponentialBackoffPolicy().label: createExponentialBackoffPolicy()
